If you hardcode a path like source ~/dotfiles/bash/bash_aliases inside your .bashrc, you lose the "portability" that makes Stow great. If you ever move your dotfiles folder or rename it, your shell breaks.

However, if you are okay with that small trade-off for a cleaner ~ directory, here is how you do it efficiently.

The "Clean Home" Strategy
In this setup, GNU Stow only manages one single file: your .bashrc. Everything else stays tucked away inside your dotfiles folder.

1. Your Folder Structure
Keep your "source" files inside the bash folder, but name them without the leading dot so Stow doesn't try to put them in your home root if you change your mind later.

Plaintext
dotfiles/
└── bash/
    ├── .bashrc          <-- Stow links this to ~/.bashrc
    ├── aliases          <-- Stays hidden inside dotfiles/bash/
    └── functions        <-- Stays hidden inside dotfiles/bash/
2. The "Smart Source" Logic
Inside your dotfiles/bash/.bashrc, you can use a bit of Bash logic to find where the "real" file lives and source its neighbors. This avoids hardcoding ~/dotfiles.

Bash
# Get the physical directory where this script actually lives
# (Even if it's being called via a symlink in ~)
DOT_DIR=$(dirname "$(readlink -f "$BASH_SOURCE")")

# Now source the other files from that same physical directory
if [ -f "$DOT_DIR/aliases" ]; then
    . "$DOT_DIR/aliases"
fi

if [ -f "$DOT_DIR/functions" ]; then
    . "$DOT_DIR/functions"
fi
Why this is better than realpath
Dynamic: If you move dotfiles from ~/dotfiles to ~/src/config, the script automatically finds the new path because it follows the symlink back to the source.

Encapsulated: Your ~ stays pristine. Only .bashrc (and maybe .bash_profile) will ever appear there.

Stow-Friendly: You still run stow bash, but since the other files don't have a . prefix or a matching path, Stow ignores them and they don't appear in your home directory.

