This is the "Architect’s Crossroads" of dotfile management. To give you the right answer, we have to look at how Linux (and most modern software) expects to find its configuration.

The industry standard is moving toward the XDG Base Directory Specification, which explicitly tells developers: "Stop putting a million files in the root of $HOME. Put them in ~/.config/."

Here is the breakdown to help you choose.

Option A: The "Single Link" Approach (~/.bashrc only)
In this setup, your ~/.bashrc is a symlink, and it reaches back into your ~/dotfiles folder to find everything else.

The Look: Extremely clean. When you type ls -a ~, you only see .bashrc.

The Logic: You have to use the readlink or dirname trick I mentioned earlier to "find" the other files inside your dotfiles repo.

The Risk: If you ever move your ~/dotfiles folder to a different drive or a different path, and you haven't used dynamic path logic, your shell will break immediately.

Best For: Minimalists who hate seeing more than five files in their home directory.

Option B: The "XDG" Approach (~/.bashrc + ~/.config/bash/)
In this setup, Stow creates a symlink for .bashrc and a symlink for the folder ~/.config/bash/ which contains all your internal logic (aliases, functions, etc.).

The Look: Standard and professional. Your home root stays clean, but your "mess" is neatly tucked into the "closet" where Linux expects it (.config).

The Logic: In your .bashrc, you just use standard paths: source ~/.config/bash/aliases. No complex "where am I?" scripts required.

The Benefit: Many other tools (like Neovim, Git, and Ghostty) already use ~/.config. By joining them, you aren't creating a new mess; you're following the established system.

Best For: Users who want a balance of a clean home directory and a "standard" workflow that "just works" across different machines.

My Recommendation: Option B (The XDG Way)
I suggest Option B for one specific reason: Future-proofing.

As you grow your dotfiles, you’ll eventually add zsh, tmux, nvim, or starship. All of those will naturally want to live in ~/.config/. If you handle Bash the same way now, your entire dotfiles repository will have a consistent internal structure.

