    └── .config/
        └── bash/            # Stowed to ~/.config/bash/
            ├── aliases
            ├── functions
            └── prompt
Why this is a "Pro Move":
When you run stow bash, Stow sees the .config folder. If ~/.config already exists (which it likely does), Stow won't overwrite it; it will simply go inside it and create the bash symlink.

Result:

~/.bashrc -> dotfiles/bash/.bashrc

~/.config/bash/ -> dotfiles/bash/.config/bash/

Your home directory remains "pristine" because .config is already a "hidden" system folder.

