You’ve hit on a classic debate in the developer community: Automation vs. Explicit Control.

To answer your question directly: No, automatic inclusion (looping through a folder) is usually not the best idea for a .bashrc.

You are right to be skeptical. Here is why staying explicit (manually listing your includes) is the smarter move for most people.

Why "Explicit" is usually better than "Automatic"
Load Order Matters: In Bash, the order in which you load things can be critical. You might want your environment_variables loaded before your aliases, or your colors loaded before your prompt. A loop just grabs things alphabetically, which can cause weird bugs.

Debugging Nightmares: If your shell starts acting up or throwing an error on startup, an explicit list tells you exactly where to look. With a loop, you have to hunt through every file in the directory to find the culprit.

Temporary Files: Sometimes you might want to drop a "test" script or a backup file (like aliases.bak) into your config folder. An automatic loop would source that backup file, potentially breaking your aliases or causing duplicates.

The "Visibility" Factor: Like you said, seeing source ~/.config/bash/aliases at the top of your .bashrc acts as a map of your system. It's much easier to manage.

The "Clean & Explicit" Setup
If you go with the Option B (XDG) structure we discussed, your .bashrc becomes a very clean "Table of Contents." It would look something like this:

Bash
# ~/.bashrc

# 1. Path & Environment
source ~/.config/bash/env

# 2. Interactive Shell Settings (History, completion, etc.)
source ~/.config/bash/options

# 3. Aliases
source ~/.config/bash/aliases

# 4. Custom Functions
source ~/.config/bash/functions

# 5. Prompt (The look of the terminal)
source ~/.config/bash/prompt
How this looks in your Dotfiles folder
Using GNU Stow with this explicit approach is very tidy. Since you are explicitly calling the files in ~/.config/bash/, Stow handles the "plumbing" and you handle the "logic."

Plaintext
dotfiles/
└── bash/
    ├── .bashrc               # Becomes ~/.bashrc
    └── .config/
        └── bash/             # Becomes ~/.config/bash/
            ├── aliases       # (Explicitly sourced)
            ├── env           # (Explicitly sourced)
            ├── functions     # (Explicitly sourced)
            └── prompt        # (Explicitly sourced)
The Verdict
Stick to explicit sourcing. It takes 10 seconds longer to set up, but it saves you hours of head-scratching later when you're trying to figure out why a certain alias isn't working or why your path is being overwritten.

